{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c5ae3392-4d65-467e-a356-7cfa7fc3fce8","content":"With **MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0**, the switch is straightforward. In your project file:\n\n**Remove (or set to `false`):**\n```xml\n<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>\n```\n\n**That's it.** MSTest.Sdk defaults to Microsoft.Testing.Platform when `UseVSTest` is not set to `true`. Removing the property (or explicitly setting it to `false`) enables the new platform automatically.\n\n### Key behavioral differences to be aware of:\n\n1. **Running tests** — Use `dotnet test` as before, but you can also run the test project directly (`dotnet run`) since the new platform produces an executable entry point.\n2. **CLI options** — VSTest options like `--filter` still work, but the new platform also supports `--filter` natively with its own syntax. Check `dotnet test --help` for details.\n3. **`.runsettings`** — Still supported, but some VSTest-specific adapter settings may not apply.\n4. **Test output** — The console output format changes slightly (new platform's default reporter).\n\n### If you hit issues:\n\n- Ensure any third-party test extensions/adapters you use are compatible with Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n- If you explicitly reference `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk`, remove it — MSTest.Sdk manages that dependency.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b8e3d32d-6d3b-49b3-b2d8-8c753f83547f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The working directory is empty and there's no relevant documentation in the repository. Let me answer based on my knowledge of MSTest.Sdk and the migration from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform.","outputTokens":371,"requestId":"4814:12FCC3:3185151:361B49A:69FBE2FD"},"id":"03a5612e-1908-4e71-911b-d7238523c0fc","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:55:35.926Z","parentId":"985879c1-79e6-4ead-bbbf-9db9d878af0c"}
